INSERT INTO knowledge_patterns (id, clause_pattern, category, contract_type, risk_level, why_risky, safer_alternative, jurisdiction_notes, embedding, created_at) VALUES ('c3c9d0e1-f2a3-4b4c-9d6e-8f9a0b1c2d3e', 'The Receiving Party shall not disclose any Confidential Information to any third party for any reason whatsoever. The Receiving Party acknowledges that there are no exceptions to this obligation, and no disclosure shall be permitted under judicial, administrative, or legislative process, compulsion, or request.', 'carve_outs', '["nda"]'::jsonb, 'red', 'This clause purports to override the legal system itself: it says you can''t disclose information even if a court orders you to via a subpoena (a legal demand for information). You cannot contractually agree to defy a court order — that would put you in contempt of court, which can result in fines or jail time. Any NDA that tries to prevent legally compelled disclosure is unenforceable on that point and signals the drafter is either incompetent or deliberately overreaching.', 'The Receiving Party may disclose Confidential Information to the extent required by law, regulation, or valid court order or subpoena, provided that the Receiving Party (a) gives the Disclosing Party prompt written notice of such requirement (to the extent legally permitted), (b) cooperates with the Disclosing Party''s reasonable efforts to obtain a protective order or other appropriate remedy, and (c) discloses only that portion of the Confidential Information that is legally required to be disclosed.', 'US: Courts universally recognize that contractual provisions cannot override judicial compulsion. Federal Rules of Civil Procedure Rule 45 (subpoena power). DTSA 18 U.S.C. Section 1833(b) provides immunity for disclosures to government officials. EU: Trade Secrets Directive 2016/943 Article 5 explicitly permits disclosure required or allowed by EU or national law. UK: Trade Secrets Regulations 2018 reg. 5 — disclosure required by law is 